// FinLearnX – Unique Free Course Content (15 pages each)
// Basic: 6 courses | Intermediate: 6 courses
// All content is unique, topic-specific, non-duplicated

export const FREE_CONTENT = {};

// ─── BASIC: PERSONAL FINANCE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
FREE_CONTENT['personal-finance'] = [
  { pg:1, title:'What is Personal Finance?', sub:'Taking Control of Your Financial Life', body:`Personal finance is the management of your money — how you earn it, spend it, save it, invest it, and protect it. It is the foundation of financial well-being and the starting point for building wealth.\n\nMost people never learn personal finance in school. They learn by trial and error — often making expensive mistakes. This course changes that.\n\nThe 5 Pillars of Personal Finance:\n1. Earning: Maximizing your income through career growth and side income\n2. Spending: Controlling expenses and avoiding wasteful spending\n3. Saving: Building financial security through consistent saving\n4. Investing: Growing wealth through smart investment decisions\n5. Protecting: Insurance, emergency funds, and risk management\n\nWhy Personal Finance Matters:\nA person earning ₹50,000/month who manages money well will be wealthier at 50 than a person earning ₹2,00,000/month who manages money poorly. Income is important, but financial management is more important.`, points:['Personal finance = Managing how you earn, spend, save, invest, protect','5 pillars: Earning, Spending, Saving, Investing, Protecting','Financial management matters more than income level','Most people never learn personal finance formally — this is your advantage','Taking control of your finances is the single most impactful life decision'], highlight:'💡 "Personal finance is 80% behavior and 20% knowledge." — Dave Ramsey. The knowledge is simple; the behavior is the challenge.', example:'Two friends: Rahul earns ₹80,000/month but spends ₹78,000. Priya earns ₹50,000/month but saves ₹15,000. After 20 years at 12% return: Rahul has ₹5 Lakhs. Priya has ₹1.5 Crore.' },
  { pg:2, title:'Understanding Your Income', sub:'Know Every Rupee Coming In', body:`Before you can manage money, you need to understand exactly how much money you have. Most people have a vague idea of their income but do not know the precise numbers.\n\nTypes of Income:\n\n1. Active Income (Earned Income):\nMoney you earn by working — salary, freelance income, business income.\nCharacteristic: Stops when you stop working.\n\n2. Passive Income:\nMoney that flows in without direct time investment — rental income, dividends, royalties.\nCharacteristic: Continues even when you are not working.\n\n3. Portfolio Income:\nReturns from investments — capital gains, interest, dividends.\n\nGross Income vs Net Income:\n- Gross Income: Total income before deductions\n- Net Income (Take-Home): Income after taxes, PF, and other deductions\n\nAlways budget based on NET income, not gross income. Many people make the mistake of planning based on their CTC (Cost to Company) rather than their actual take-home pay.`, points:['Active income stops when you stop working — build passive income','Always budget based on net (take-home) income, not gross/CTC','Track all income sources — salary, freelance, interest, dividends','Passive income is the key to financial freedom','Most people underestimate their actual take-home pay'], highlight:'💡 Your CTC of ₹12 LPA does not mean ₹1 Lakh/month take-home. After taxes, PF, and deductions, it might be ₹75,000-80,000. Always know your actual net income.', example:'Arjun\'s CTC: ₹12 LPA. Actual take-home after tax (30% slab), PF (12%), and other deductions: ₹72,000/month. He was budgeting based on ₹1 Lakh — no wonder he was always short!' },
  { pg:3, title:'Tracking Your Expenses', sub:'Where Does Your Money Actually Go?', body:`Most people have no idea where their money goes. They earn a good salary but somehow reach the end of the month with nothing left. Expense tracking solves this mystery.\n\nThe 30-Day Expense Audit:\nFor one month, record every single expense — no matter how small. Use a notebook, spreadsheet, or app like Walnut or Money Manager.\n\nExpense Categories:\n- Fixed Expenses: Same every month (rent, EMI, insurance, subscriptions)\n- Variable Necessities: Change monthly but essential (groceries, utilities, transport)\n- Discretionary: Optional spending (dining out, entertainment, shopping)\n- Irregular: Occasional large expenses (medical, travel, gifts)\n\nWhat You Will Discover:\nMost people are shocked by their expense audit. Common findings:\n- ₹3,000-5,000/month on food delivery apps\n- ₹2,000-4,000/month on subscriptions they forgot about\n- ₹5,000-10,000/month on impulse purchases\n- ₹1,000-2,000/month on ATM fees and bank charges`, points:['Track every expense for 30 days — you will be shocked by the results','Categorize: Fixed, Variable Necessities, Discretionary, Irregular','Most people spend ₹5,000-15,000/month on things they do not value','Expense tracking is the foundation of all financial improvement','Use apps like Walnut, Money Manager, or a simple spreadsheet'], highlight:'💡 "You cannot manage what you do not measure." Track your expenses for just 30 days and you will find ₹5,000-15,000 in savings opportunities.', example:'Sneha\'s 30-day expense audit revealed: ₹4,200 on food delivery, ₹2,800 on unused subscriptions, ₹6,500 on impulse shopping. Total waste: ₹13,500/month = ₹1.62 Lakhs/year.' },
  { pg:4, title:'Net Worth — Your Financial Scoreboard', sub:'The One Number That Measures Your Financial Health', body:`Net worth is the single most important number in personal finance. It is your financial scoreboard — the true measure of your wealth.\n\nNet Worth Formula:\nNet Worth = Total Assets − Total Liabilities\n\nAssets (What You Own):\n- Cash and bank balances\n- Investments (stocks, mutual funds, FDs)\n- Real estate (market value)\n- Gold and jewelry\n- Vehicle value\n- EPF/PPF balance\n\nLiabilities (What You Owe):\n- Home loan outstanding\n- Car loan outstanding\n- Personal loan outstanding\n- Credit card outstanding balance\n- Any other debt\n\nWhy Track Net Worth:\n- Shows your true financial progress\n- Motivates better financial decisions\n- Reveals if you are building or destroying wealth\n- Helps identify problem areas (too much debt, too little investment)`, points:['Net Worth = Total Assets − Total Liabilities','Track net worth monthly to measure financial progress','Positive net worth = building wealth; Negative = destroying wealth','Focus on growing assets and reducing liabilities simultaneously','Net worth should grow every month — if not, something is wrong'], highlight:'💡 Your salary is your income. Your net worth is your wealth. A high salary with high debt = low net worth. A moderate salary with smart investing = high net worth.', example:'Vikram (age 35): Salary ₹1.5L/month. Assets: ₹45L (investments + property). Liabilities: ₹38L (home loan + car loan). Net Worth: ₹7L. Needs urgent improvement despite high income.' },
  { pg:5, title:'Setting Financial Goals', sub:'The SMART Framework for Money Goals', body:`Without clear financial goals, money management is aimless. Goals give your financial decisions direction and purpose.\n\nThe SMART Goal Framework:\n\nS — Specific: "Save ₹10 Lakhs for home down payment" (not "save more money")\nM — Measurable: Track progress monthly with exact numbers\nA — Achievable: Realistic given your income and expenses\nR — Relevant: Aligned with your life values and priorities\nT — Time-bound: "By December 2027" (not "someday")\n\nThree Categories of Financial Goals:\n\nShort-Term (0-2 years):\n- Emergency fund (3-6 months expenses)\n- Debt payoff\n- Vacation fund\n\nMedium-Term (2-7 years):\n- Home down payment\n- Car purchase\n- Child's education fund\n\nLong-Term (7+ years):\n- Retirement corpus\n- Financial independence\n- Wealth creation`, points:['SMART goals: Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, Time-bound','Short-term: Emergency fund, debt payoff (0-2 years)','Medium-term: Home, car, education (2-7 years)','Long-term: Retirement, financial independence (7+ years)','Write goals down — written goals are 42% more likely to be achieved'], highlight:'💡 "A goal without a plan is just a wish." Write your top 3 financial goals today with specific amounts and deadlines.', example:'Meera\'s SMART Goal: "Save ₹8 Lakhs for home down payment by March 2027 by investing ₹15,000/month in a hybrid mutual fund." Specific, measurable, achievable, relevant, time-bound.' },
  { pg:6, title:'The Money Mindset', sub:'How Your Beliefs About Money Shape Your Finances', body:`Your relationship with money is shaped by your upbringing, experiences, and beliefs. These "money scripts" — often unconscious — drive your financial behavior.\n\nCommon Negative Money Scripts:\n1. "Money is the root of all evil" → Subconsciously avoid accumulating wealth\n2. "Rich people are greedy" → Feel guilty about wanting more money\n3. "I am not good with money" → Self-fulfilling prophecy of financial failure\n4. "Money cannot buy happiness" → Excuse to not manage money well\n5. "I will start saving when I earn more" → Perpetual delay\n\nPositive Money Mindset Shifts:\n- Money is a tool — neutral, neither good nor evil\n- Wealth enables you to help yourself and others\n- Financial skills can be learned by anyone\n- Small amounts invested consistently create massive wealth\n- The best time to start is now, not later\n\nThe Abundance vs Scarcity Mindset:\nScarcity: "There is never enough money"\nAbundance: "Money is a renewable resource — I can always earn more"`, points:['Your money beliefs (scripts) drive your financial behavior','Identify and challenge negative money scripts','Money is a neutral tool — it amplifies who you already are','Abundance mindset: Money is renewable, opportunities are everywhere','Financial skills are learned, not innate — anyone can improve'], highlight:'💡 "Whether you think you can or you think you cannot — you are right." Your money mindset is a self-fulfilling prophecy. Choose abundance.', example:'Two colleagues with same salary: Ravi believes "I am not good with money" — never invests, always broke. Anita believes "I can learn to manage money" — reads, learns, invests. 10 years later: completely different financial lives.' },
  { pg:7, title:'Emergency Fund — Your Financial Safety Net', sub:'The Foundation of Financial Security', body:`An emergency fund is money set aside specifically for unexpected expenses or income loss. It is the most important first step in personal finance — before investing, before paying extra on debt.\n\nWhy Emergency Fund First:\n- Without it, any unexpected expense becomes a financial crisis\n- Forces you to take on high-interest debt (credit cards, personal loans)\n- Creates financial stress that affects all other decisions\n- Prevents you from selling investments at the wrong time\n\nHow Much to Save:\n- Minimum: 3 months of essential expenses\n- Recommended: 6 months of essential expenses\n- If self-employed or variable income: 9-12 months\n\nWhere to Keep Emergency Fund:\n- High-yield savings account (4-5% interest)\n- Liquid mutual fund (better returns, same-day withdrawal)\n- NOT in stocks or long-term investments\n\nBuilding Your Emergency Fund:\n- Start with ₹10,000 as a mini emergency fund\n- Build to 1 month expenses, then 3 months, then 6 months\n- Automate a fixed transfer every month`, points:['Emergency fund = 3-6 months of essential expenses','Build emergency fund BEFORE investing or paying extra debt','Keep in liquid fund or high-yield savings — NOT in stocks','Start with ₹10,000 mini emergency fund, then build up','Replenish immediately after using it'], highlight:'💡 An emergency fund does not earn high returns — that is not its job. Its job is to be there when you need it, preventing financial disasters.', example:'Karan had no emergency fund. His car broke down — ₹45,000 repair. He put it on credit card at 36% interest. Paid ₹3,000/month for 18 months = ₹54,000 total. Emergency fund would have saved ₹9,000.' },
  { pg:8, title:'Understanding Insurance', sub:'Protecting What You Have Built', body:`Insurance is risk management — paying a small, certain amount (premium) to protect against a large, uncertain loss. It is not an investment; it is protection.\n\nEssential Insurance Types:\n\n1. Term Life Insurance:\n- Pays a lump sum to your family if you die\n- Pure protection — no investment component\n- Cheapest way to provide financial security for dependents\n- Rule: Cover = 10-15x annual income\n- Example: ₹1 Crore term plan for 30-year-old = ₹8,000-12,000/year\n\n2. Health Insurance:\n- Covers medical expenses\n- Most critical insurance — medical costs can be devastating\n- Minimum: ₹5 Lakh individual cover\n- Recommended: ₹10-25 Lakh family floater\n\n3. Critical Illness Insurance:\n- Lump sum payment on diagnosis of serious illness\n- Covers income loss during treatment\n\nInsurance Mistakes to Avoid:\n- Mixing insurance with investment (ULIPs, endowment plans)\n- Underinsuring to save premium\n- Not reading policy terms`, points:['Term life insurance: 10-15x annual income coverage','Health insurance: Minimum ₹5 Lakh, recommended ₹10-25 Lakh','Never mix insurance with investment — buy pure term + invest separately','Insurance is protection, not investment — do not expect returns','Review insurance coverage annually as income and family grows'], highlight:'💡 A ₹1 Crore term plan for a 30-year-old costs ₹8,000-12,000/year. That is ₹700-1,000/month to ensure your family is financially secure if something happens to you.', example:'Rohit (age 32, income ₹10L/year) has no term insurance. He dies in an accident. His family has no income. With ₹1 Crore term plan (cost: ₹10,000/year), family gets ₹1 Crore — 10 years of income.' },
  { pg:9, title:'Banking Basics', sub:'Making Your Bank Account Work for You', body:`Most people use their bank account as a simple storage facility. Smart banking means making your money work harder even while it sits in the bank.\n\nTypes of Bank Accounts:\n\n1. Savings Account:\n- Standard account for daily transactions\n- Interest: 2.5-4% (varies by bank)\n- Tip: Keep only 1-2 months expenses here\n\n2. Fixed Deposit (FD):\n- Lock money for fixed period at higher interest (6-7.5%)\n- Best for: Emergency fund portion, short-term goals\n- Premature withdrawal penalty: 0.5-1%\n\n3. Recurring Deposit (RD):\n- Fixed monthly deposit for fixed period\n- Interest: Similar to FD\n- Good for: Building savings habit\n\nSmart Banking Tips:\n- Maintain minimum balance to avoid charges\n- Use zero-balance accounts (Jan Dhan, digital banks)\n- Avoid ATM fees — use your bank's ATMs\n- Set up auto-pay for bills to avoid late fees\n- Use credit card for purchases (earn rewards) but pay full balance monthly`, points:['Keep only 1-2 months expenses in savings account','FD for emergency fund and short-term goals (6-7.5% interest)','Zero-balance accounts (digital banks) eliminate minimum balance charges','Auto-pay bills to avoid late fees and credit score damage','Credit card rewards are free money — if you pay full balance monthly'], highlight:'💡 Keeping ₹5 Lakhs in a savings account at 3.5% vs liquid fund at 6.5% = ₹15,000 difference per year. Small optimizations compound significantly.', example:'Divya moved her ₹3 Lakh emergency fund from savings account (3.5%) to liquid mutual fund (6.5%). Extra return: ₹9,000/year. Over 10 years at reinvested returns: ₹1.2 Lakhs extra — for zero extra effort.' },
  { pg:10, title:'Debt Management Basics', sub:'Understanding Good Debt vs Bad Debt', body:`Not all debt is equal. Understanding the difference between good debt and bad debt is crucial for financial health.\n\nGood Debt:\nDebt used to acquire assets that appreciate or generate income.\n- Home loan: Property appreciates, builds equity\n- Education loan: Increases earning potential\n- Business loan: Generates income\nCharacteristic: Low interest rate, tax benefits, builds wealth\n\nBad Debt:\nDebt used to buy depreciating assets or consumables.\n- Credit card debt: 24-42% interest rate\n- Personal loan for vacation: 12-18% interest\n- Car loan: Vehicle depreciates immediately\n- Buy Now Pay Later (BNPL): Often high hidden charges\nCharacteristic: High interest rate, no tax benefit, destroys wealth\n\nDebt Payoff Strategies:\n\n1. Avalanche Method: Pay highest interest rate debt first (mathematically optimal)\n2. Snowball Method: Pay smallest balance first (psychologically motivating)\n\nDebt-to-Income Ratio:\nTotal monthly debt payments ÷ Monthly income × 100\nHealthy: Below 36% | Warning: 36-50% | Danger: Above 50%`, points:['Good debt: Low interest, builds assets or income (home loan, education)','Bad debt: High interest, buys depreciating items (credit card, personal loan)','Credit card debt at 36% is the most destructive financial force','Avalanche method: Pay highest interest first (saves most money)','Debt-to-income ratio below 36% is healthy'], highlight:'💡 ₹1 Lakh credit card debt at 36% annual interest: If you pay only minimum (2%), it takes 22 years to pay off and costs ₹3.8 Lakhs in interest. Pay it off immediately.', example:'Amit has ₹50,000 credit card debt (36% interest) and ₹2 Lakh personal loan (14% interest). Avalanche method: Pay off credit card first (saves ₹18,000 in interest vs snowball method).' },
  { pg:11, title:'Tax Basics for Individuals', sub:'Keep More of What You Earn', body:`Understanding basic tax concepts helps you legally minimize your tax burden and keep more of your hard-earned money.\n\nIncome Tax Slabs (New Regime FY2024-25):\n- Up to ₹3 Lakh: Nil\n- ₹3-6 Lakh: 5%\n- ₹6-9 Lakh: 10%\n- ₹9-12 Lakh: 15%\n- ₹12-15 Lakh: 20%\n- Above ₹15 Lakh: 30%\n\nKey Tax-Saving Investments (Old Regime):\n- Section 80C: Up to ₹1.5 Lakh deduction\n  (ELSS, PPF, EPF, NSC, home loan principal, life insurance)\n- Section 80D: Health insurance premium (up to ₹25,000)\n- Section 80CCD(1B): NPS additional ₹50,000 deduction\n- Home loan interest: Up to ₹2 Lakh deduction (Section 24)\n\nNew vs Old Regime:\n- New Regime: Lower rates, no deductions\n- Old Regime: Higher rates, but deductions available\n- For most salaried with investments: Old regime saves more tax`, points:['New tax regime: Lower rates but no deductions','Old tax regime: Higher rates but ₹1.5L+ deductions available','Section 80C: ₹1.5 Lakh deduction (ELSS, PPF, EPF, insurance)','Section 80D: Health insurance premium deduction','NPS: Additional ₹50,000 deduction under 80CCD(1B)'], highlight:'💡 Investing ₹1.5 Lakh in ELSS (Section 80C) saves ₹46,800 in tax (30% slab) while also growing your wealth. It is the best tax-saving investment.', example:'Priya (30% tax slab) invests ₹1.5L in ELSS + ₹50,000 in NPS = ₹2L total deduction. Tax saved: ₹62,400. Plus ELSS grows at 14% CAGR. Double benefit: tax saving + wealth creation.' },
  { pg:12, title:'Building Multiple Income Streams', sub:'Why One Income Source Is Never Enough', body:`Relying on a single income source is financially risky. Job loss, health issues, or economic downturns can eliminate your only income overnight.\n\nThe Income Diversification Framework:\n\nLevel 1 — Primary Income:\nYour main job or business. Maximize this through skill development and career growth.\n\nLevel 2 — Side Income:\nFreelancing, consulting, part-time work in your area of expertise.\nGoal: 20-30% of primary income\n\nLevel 3 — Passive Income:\nIncome that requires minimal ongoing effort:\n- Rental income from property\n- Dividend income from stocks\n- Interest from FDs and bonds\n- Royalties from content, books, courses\n\nLevel 4 — Portfolio Income:\nCapital gains from investments.\n\nStarting Your Second Income:\n- Identify your most marketable skill\n- Start with 5-10 hours/week\n- Reinvest all side income initially\n- Build to replace primary income over 3-5 years`, points:['Single income source = high financial risk','Side income goal: 20-30% of primary income','Passive income: Rental, dividends, interest, royalties','Start with your most marketable skill for side income','Reinvest all side income initially to accelerate wealth building'], highlight:'💡 "Never depend on a single income. Make investment to create a second source." — Warren Buffett. Even ₹5,000/month side income = ₹60,000/year = ₹18 Lakhs over 20 years at 12%.', example:'Software engineer Kiran starts freelancing on weekends: ₹15,000/month extra. Invests all of it in equity SIP. After 15 years at 14% CAGR: ₹1.1 Crore from side income alone.' },
  { pg:13, title:'Financial Mistakes to Avoid', sub:'Learn from Others\' Expensive Errors', body:`The most expensive financial education is learning from your own mistakes. Here are the most common financial mistakes and how to avoid them.\n\nMistake 1 — No Emergency Fund:\nResult: Any unexpected expense becomes a debt crisis.\nFix: Build 3-6 months expenses in liquid fund before anything else.\n\nMistake 2 — Lifestyle Inflation:\nResult: Income doubles but savings stay the same.\nFix: Save/invest at least 50% of every income increase.\n\nMistake 3 — Mixing Insurance with Investment:\nResult: Overpaying for poor returns (ULIPs, endowment plans).\nFix: Buy pure term insurance + invest separately in mutual funds.\n\nMistake 4 — Delaying Investing:\nResult: Missing years of compounding — the most costly mistake.\nFix: Start with ₹500/month today. Amount matters less than starting.\n\nMistake 5 — Following Tips and Rumors:\nResult: Buying overvalued stocks based on WhatsApp forwards.\nFix: Invest in index funds or do proper research.\n\nMistake 6 — No Financial Goals:\nResult: Spending without purpose, no wealth accumulation.\nFix: Write 3 specific financial goals with amounts and deadlines.`, points:['No emergency fund = every crisis becomes a debt crisis','Lifestyle inflation: Save 50% of every income increase','Never mix insurance with investment — buy pure term + invest separately','Delaying investing by 10 years can cost you 3-5x in final corpus','Never invest based on tips — use index funds or do proper research'], highlight:'💡 The most expensive financial mistake is not starting to invest early. Every year of delay costs you approximately 15-20% of your final retirement corpus.', example:'Starting SIP at 25 vs 35 (₹10,000/month at 12%): Age 25 start = ₹6.4 Crore at 60. Age 35 start = ₹1.9 Crore at 60. The 10-year delay costs ₹4.5 Crore — the most expensive mistake.' },
  { pg:14, title:'Creating Your Personal Finance Plan', sub:'A Step-by-Step Blueprint', body:`A personal finance plan is your roadmap to financial success. Here is how to create one in 6 steps.\n\nStep 1 — Know Your Numbers:\n- Monthly net income: ₹___\n- Monthly essential expenses: ₹___\n- Monthly discretionary expenses: ₹___\n- Current savings rate: ____%\n- Current net worth: ₹___\n\nStep 2 — Set Your Goals:\n- Emergency fund target: ₹___ by ___\n- Short-term goal: ₹___ by ___\n- Long-term goal: ₹___ by ___\n\nStep 3 — Create Your Budget:\n- Apply 50/30/20 rule or zero-based budgeting\n- Automate savings before spending\n\nStep 4 — Build Emergency Fund:\n- Open liquid fund account\n- Set up ₹5,000-10,000/month auto-transfer\n\nStep 5 — Start Investing:\n- Open Zerodha or Groww account\n- Start Nifty 50 Index Fund SIP\n\nStep 6 — Review Monthly:\n- Track net worth\n- Review budget vs actual\n- Adjust as needed`, points:['Know your exact numbers: income, expenses, savings rate, net worth','Set 3 specific financial goals with amounts and deadlines','Automate savings before spending — pay yourself first','Build emergency fund before investing','Review monthly: net worth, budget vs actual, goal progress'], highlight:'💡 A financial plan does not need to be complex. One page with your income, expenses, goals, and investment plan is enough to transform your finances.', example:'Ananya\'s one-page plan: Income ₹60,000. Expenses ₹35,000. Savings ₹25,000 (42% rate). Goals: Emergency fund ₹2L (6 months), Home down payment ₹15L by 2028, Retirement ₹3 Crore by 2050.' },
  { pg:15, title:'Personal Finance Action Plan', sub:'Start Today — Your 30-Day Financial Transformation', body:`You have completed the Introduction to Personal Finance course. Now it is time to act. Knowledge without action is worthless.\n\nYour 30-Day Action Plan:\n\nDay 1-7 — Foundation:\n✓ Calculate your exact monthly net income\n✓ Track every expense for 7 days\n✓ Calculate your current net worth\n✓ Write 3 SMART financial goals\n\nDay 8-14 — Setup:\n✓ Open a liquid fund account (Groww, Zerodha Coin)\n✓ Start ₹5,000/month emergency fund SIP\n✓ Review all subscriptions — cancel unused ones\n✓ Check if you have adequate term and health insurance\n\nDay 15-21 — Optimize:\n✓ Create a monthly budget using 50/30/20 rule\n✓ Set up auto-pay for all bills\n✓ Open a Zerodha or Groww account for investing\n✓ Start ₹1,000/month Nifty 50 Index Fund SIP\n\nDay 22-30 — Habits:\n✓ Set up monthly net worth tracking spreadsheet\n✓ Schedule monthly financial review (1st of each month)\n✓ Read one personal finance article per week\n✓ Take the quiz to earn your completion badge\n\nRemember: Perfect is the enemy of good. Start imperfectly today.`, points:['Calculate net income, track expenses, compute net worth — this week','Open liquid fund for emergency fund — this week','Start ₹1,000/month Nifty 50 Index Fund SIP — this month','Set up monthly financial review on 1st of each month','Take the quiz to earn your Personal Finance badge'], highlight:'💡 "The journey of a thousand miles begins with a single step." Your financial transformation begins with one action today — not tomorrow, not next month. Today.', example:'Students who complete this course and take one action within 24 hours are 10x more likely to achieve their financial goals than those who wait. What is your one action today?' },
];

// ─── BASIC: SAVING STRATEGIES ────────────────────────────────────────────────
FREE_CONTENT['saving-strategies'] = [
  { pg:1, title:'Why Saving Matters', sub:'The Foundation of All Wealth', body:`Saving is the act of setting aside money today for future use. It is the bridge between your current financial situation and your financial goals. Without saving, there is no investing, no wealth, no financial freedom.\n\nThe Saving Paradox:\nMost people think they will save "what is left over" after spending. This never works. There is never anything left over. The correct approach: Save first, then spend what remains.\n\nThe Savings Rate — The Most Important Number:\nYour savings rate (savings ÷ income × 100) determines how quickly you build wealth. It is more important than your investment returns.\n\nSavings Rate and Years to Financial Independence:\n- 10% savings rate: 43 years to financial independence\n- 20% savings rate: 37 years\n- 30% savings rate: 28 years\n- 50% savings rate: 17 years\n- 70% savings rate: 8.5 years\n\nThe math is clear: Increasing your savings rate is the fastest path to financial freedom.`, points:['Save first, spend what remains — never the reverse','Savings rate is more important than investment returns','10% savings rate = 43 years to financial independence','50% savings rate = 17 years to financial independence','Every 1% increase in savings rate accelerates your timeline significantly'], highlight:'💡 "Do not save what is left after spending; instead spend what is left after saving." — Warren Buffett. This one mindset shift changes everything.', example:'Raj saves 10% of ₹60,000 = ₹6,000/month. Priya saves 30% = ₹18,000/month. At 12% return over 20 years: Raj = ₹59.9L. Priya = ₹1.8 Crore. Same income, 3x savings rate = 3x wealth.' },
  { pg:2, title:'Pay Yourself First', sub:'The Most Powerful Saving Strategy', body:`"Pay Yourself First" is the most powerful saving strategy ever discovered. It means treating your savings like a non-negotiable bill — the first payment you make every month, before anything else.\n\nHow It Works:\n1. Decide your savings amount (start with 10%, aim for 20-30%)\n2. On payday, immediately transfer that amount to a separate savings/investment account\n3. Live on what remains\n\nWhy It Works:\n- Removes the temptation to spend savings\n- Savings happen automatically, not by willpower\n- You adapt your lifestyle to what remains\n- Eliminates the "I will save what is left" trap\n\nImplementation:\n- Set up auto-transfer on the same day as salary credit\n- Use a separate account that is slightly inconvenient to access\n- Start with 10% and increase by 1% every 3 months\n\nThe Latte Factor:\nSmall daily savings compound to enormous amounts. ₹200/day saved = ₹6,000/month = ₹72,000/year. Invested at 12% for 20 years = ₹65 Lakhs from just ₹200/day.`, points:['Pay yourself first: Save before spending, not after','Set up auto-transfer on payday to separate savings account','Start with 10%, increase by 1% every 3 months','Small daily savings compound to enormous wealth over time','₹200/day saved and invested = ₹65 Lakhs over 20 years at 12%'], highlight:'💡 The Latte Factor: ₹200/day on coffee and snacks = ₹6,000/month. Invested at 12% for 30 years = ₹2.1 Crore. Your daily habits are either building or destroying your wealth.', example:'Neha sets up auto-transfer of ₹10,000 on the 1st of every month (payday). She never misses it because it happens automatically. After 15 years at 12%: ₹50 Lakhs — built on autopilot.' },
  { pg:3, title:'The 50/30/20 Savings Rule', sub:'A Simple Framework That Works', body:`The 50/30/20 rule is the most popular budgeting framework because it is simple, flexible, and effective. It divides your after-tax income into three categories.\n\n50% — Needs (Essential Expenses):\nThings you cannot live without:\n- Rent/EMI\n- Groceries and food\n- Utilities (electricity, water, internet)\n- Transportation\n- Insurance premiums\n- Minimum debt payments\n\n30% — Wants (Lifestyle Expenses):\nThings you enjoy but could live without:\n- Dining out and food delivery\n- Entertainment (movies, OTT subscriptions)\n- Shopping (clothes, gadgets)\n- Travel and vacations\n- Gym membership\n\n20% — Savings and Investments:\n- Emergency fund\n- SIP investments\n- Retirement savings\n- Debt payoff (above minimum)\n\nFor ₹60,000/month income:\n- Needs: ₹30,000\n- Wants: ₹18,000\n- Savings: ₹12,000`, points:['50% Needs: Rent, groceries, utilities, transport, insurance','30% Wants: Dining, entertainment, shopping, travel','20% Savings: Emergency fund, SIP, retirement, debt payoff','Adjust ratios based on your situation — 50/30/20 is a starting point','If needs exceed 50%, focus on reducing fixed costs (rent, EMI)'], highlight:'💡 If your needs exceed 50% of income, you have a structural problem — either income is too low or fixed costs are too high. Address this before anything else.', example:'Arun (₹70,000/month): Needs ₹35,000 (50%), Wants ₹21,000 (30%), Savings ₹14,000 (20%). He starts SIP of ₹10,000 + emergency fund ₹4,000. Simple, sustainable, effective.' },
  { pg:4, title:'Automating Your Savings', sub:'Remove Willpower from the Equation', body:`The biggest enemy of saving is human psychology. We are wired for immediate gratification — spending feels good now, saving feels like deprivation. Automation removes psychology from the equation.\n\nThe Automation Stack:\n\nStep 1 — Salary Account:\nYour salary lands here. This is your "flow-through" account.\n\nStep 2 — Auto-Transfer on Payday:\nSet up automatic transfers on the day salary arrives:\n- Emergency fund: ₹X to liquid fund\n- Investment SIP: ₹X to mutual fund (already automated)\n- Bills: ₹X to bills account\n\nStep 3 — Spending Account:\nWhat remains after auto-transfers is your spending money. Spend freely without guilt.\n\nTools for Automation:\n- Bank standing instructions for recurring transfers\n- SIP auto-debit through mutual fund apps\n- Auto-pay for all bills and EMIs\n- Recurring deposit for short-term goals\n\nThe Psychology of Automation:\nWhen savings happen automatically, you adapt to the lower spending amount. You do not miss what you never see.`, points:['Automation removes willpower from saving — it happens regardless of mood','Set up auto-transfer on payday before you can spend the money','Automate: Emergency fund, SIP, bills, and goal-based savings','Spend freely from what remains — no guilt, no tracking needed','You adapt to lower spending amount when savings are automatic'], highlight:'💡 "Set it and forget it." The most successful savers do not rely on discipline — they rely on systems. Automate everything and let the system do the work.', example:'Kavya\'s automation: Salary ₹80,000 arrives on 1st. Auto-transfer: ₹15,000 to SIP, ₹5,000 to emergency fund, ₹20,000 to bills account. Remaining ₹40,000 for spending. Zero willpower needed.' },
  { pg:5, title:'High-Yield Savings Options', sub:'Make Your Savings Work Harder', body:`Not all savings accounts are equal. Choosing the right savings vehicle can significantly increase your returns without additional risk.\n\nSavings Options Ranked by Return:\n\n1. Regular Savings Account: 2.5-4% interest\n   Best for: Daily transactions only\n\n2. High-Yield Savings Account (Small Finance Banks): 5-7%\n   Best for: Emergency fund\n   Examples: AU Small Finance Bank (7%), ESAF Bank (6.5%)\n\n3. Liquid Mutual Fund: 6-7.5%\n   Best for: Emergency fund, short-term parking\n   Withdrawal: Same day (T+0 or T+1)\n\n4. Recurring Deposit (RD): 6-7%\n   Best for: Building savings habit, short-term goals\n\n5. Fixed Deposit (FD): 6.5-7.5%\n   Best for: 1-3 year goals\n   Note: Premature withdrawal penalty\n\n6. Debt Mutual Fund (Short Duration): 7-8%\n   Best for: 1-3 year goals\n   Tax efficient for high-income earners`, points:['Regular savings account (2.5-4%) is the worst place to keep savings','Liquid mutual fund (6-7.5%) is best for emergency fund','Small finance banks offer 5-7% on savings accounts','FD (6.5-7.5%) for 1-3 year goals','Debt mutual funds are tax-efficient for high-income earners'], highlight:'💡 Moving ₹5 Lakhs from regular savings (3.5%) to liquid fund (6.5%) = ₹15,000 extra per year. Over 10 years with reinvestment = ₹2 Lakhs extra — for zero extra effort.', example:'Comparison on ₹3 Lakh emergency fund over 5 years: Regular savings (3.5%) = ₹3.57L. Liquid fund (6.5%) = ₹4.09L. Difference = ₹52,000 — just by choosing the right savings vehicle.' },
  { pg:6, title:'Emergency Fund Strategy', sub:'Building Your Financial Safety Net Step by Step', body:`An emergency fund is not just about having money saved — it is about having the right amount, in the right place, accessible at the right time.\n\nThe 3-Tier Emergency Fund Strategy:\n\nTier 1 — Immediate Access (₹25,000-50,000):\n- Keep in savings account\n- For small emergencies: car repair, medical co-pay\n- Accessible within minutes\n\nTier 2 — Short-Term Access (1-2 months expenses):\n- Keep in liquid mutual fund\n- For medium emergencies: job loss, major medical\n- Accessible within 1 business day\n\nTier 3 — Extended Buffer (3-4 months expenses):\n- Keep in short-term FD or debt fund\n- For extended emergencies: prolonged job loss\n- Accessible within 3-5 days\n\nBuilding the Emergency Fund:\nPhase 1: Save ₹25,000 (mini emergency fund) — 1-3 months\nPhase 2: Build to 1 month expenses — 3-6 months\nPhase 3: Build to 3 months expenses — 6-12 months\nPhase 4: Build to 6 months expenses — 12-18 months`, points:['3-tier strategy: Immediate (savings), Short-term (liquid fund), Extended (FD)','Tier 1: ₹25,000-50,000 in savings account for immediate access','Tier 2: 1-2 months in liquid fund (1-day access)','Tier 3: 3-4 months in FD or debt fund (3-5 day access)','Build in phases: ₹25K → 1 month → 3 months → 6 months'], highlight:'💡 The emergency fund is not an investment — it is insurance. Its job is to be there when you need it, not to earn maximum returns.', example:'Suresh lost his job in March 2023. His 6-month emergency fund (₹3.6 Lakhs in liquid fund) gave him 6 months to find a new job without financial stress. He found a better job in 4 months.' },
  { pg:7, title:'Sinking Funds', sub:'Saving for Planned Future Expenses', body:`A sinking fund is money saved specifically for a planned future expense. Unlike an emergency fund (for unexpected events), sinking funds are for expenses you know are coming.\n\nWhy Sinking Funds:\n- Prevents large expenses from derailing your budget\n- Eliminates the need for credit card debt for planned expenses\n- Reduces financial stress around predictable costs\n\nCommon Sinking Funds:\n1. Annual expenses: Insurance premiums, property tax, car service\n2. Vacation fund: ₹500-2,000/month for annual vacation\n3. Electronics fund: ₹1,000-2,000/month for phone/laptop replacement\n4. Medical fund: ₹1,000-2,000/month for dental, glasses, etc.\n5. Gift fund: ₹500-1,000/month for festivals, birthdays, weddings\n6. Car maintenance: ₹1,000-2,000/month for repairs and service\n\nHow to Set Up Sinking Funds:\n1. List all planned future expenses\n2. Estimate annual cost\n3. Divide by 12 = monthly sinking fund amount\n4. Open separate savings account or sub-account for each\n5. Auto-transfer monthly`, points:['Sinking funds = saving for planned future expenses','Prevents large expenses from creating debt or budget disruption','Common sinking funds: vacation, electronics, medical, gifts, car','Calculate: Annual cost ÷ 12 = monthly sinking fund amount','Keep sinking funds in separate accounts to avoid spending them'], highlight:'💡 A ₹60,000 vacation feels free when you have been saving ₹5,000/month for 12 months. Sinking funds transform large expenses from stressful to painless.', example:'Meera\'s sinking funds: Vacation ₹3,000/month, Electronics ₹1,500/month, Medical ₹1,000/month, Gifts ₹1,000/month. Total: ₹6,500/month. No more credit card debt for planned expenses.' },
  { pg:8, title:'Savings Rate Optimization', sub:'How to Save More Without Earning More', body:`Most people think they need to earn more to save more. In reality, you can dramatically increase your savings rate without a salary increase by optimizing your expenses.\n\nThe Savings Rate Formula:\nSavings Rate = (Income − Expenses) ÷ Income × 100\n\nTo increase savings rate, you can:\n1. Increase income (harder, takes time)\n2. Decrease expenses (easier, immediate impact)\n\nExpense Optimization Strategies:\n\nHousing (Biggest Expense):\n- Consider house-sharing to reduce rent\n- Move to a slightly smaller apartment\n- Negotiate rent renewal\n\nFood (Second Biggest):\n- Cook at home 5 days/week\n- Meal prep on Sundays\n- Limit food delivery to 2x/week\n\nSubscriptions:\n- Audit all subscriptions monthly\n- Share accounts with family\n- Cancel anything unused for 30+ days\n\nTransportation:\n- Use public transport when possible\n- Carpool with colleagues\n- Avoid unnecessary Uber/Ola rides`, points:['Savings rate = (Income − Expenses) ÷ Income × 100','Reducing expenses has immediate impact; increasing income takes time','Housing and food are the two biggest expense categories','Subscription audit: Cancel anything unused for 30+ days','Every ₹1,000 saved monthly = ₹35 Lakhs over 20 years at 12%'], highlight:'💡 Every ₹1,000/month you save is worth ₹35 Lakhs over 20 years at 12% return. That unused Netflix subscription is not ₹200/month — it is ₹7 Lakhs over 20 years.', example:'Rahul\'s expense audit: Cancelled 4 unused subscriptions (₹1,200/month), reduced food delivery from daily to 3x/week (₹3,000/month saved), started carpooling (₹2,000/month saved). Total: ₹6,200/month extra savings.' },
  { pg:9, title:'Saving for Short-Term Goals', sub:'Building Goal-Specific Savings Accounts', body:`Short-term goals (0-3 years) require a different savings strategy than long-term goals. The key difference: capital preservation matters more than returns.\n\nShort-Term Goal Examples:\n- Emergency fund: 3-6 months expenses\n- Vacation: ₹50,000-2,00,000\n- New phone/laptop: ₹30,000-1,50,000\n- Wedding expenses: ₹2,00,000-10,00,000\n- Home down payment (3-year horizon): ₹5,00,000-20,00,000\n\nBest Savings Vehicles for Short-Term Goals:\n\n1-Year Goals:\n- Liquid fund or short-term FD\n- Returns: 6-7%\n- Risk: Very low\n\n1-3 Year Goals:\n- Short-duration debt fund or FD\n- Returns: 7-8%\n- Risk: Low\n\nDo NOT use equity for short-term goals:\n- Stock market can fall 30-50% in any given year\n- You may need to sell at a loss\n- Short-term goals need capital protection`, points:['Short-term goals (0-3 years): Capital preservation over returns','1-year goals: Liquid fund or short-term FD (6-7%)','1-3 year goals: Short-duration debt fund or FD (7-8%)','Never use equity/stocks for goals within 3 years','Separate savings account for each goal prevents mixing funds'], highlight:'💡 Never invest money you need within 3 years in the stock market. The market can fall 40% and take 2-3 years to recover. Short-term goals need safe, liquid investments.', example:'Priya saving for wedding in 2 years (₹5 Lakh target): Invests ₹18,000/month in short-duration debt fund (7.5%). After 24 months: ₹4.98 Lakhs. Goal achieved safely without stock market risk.' },
  { pg:10, title:'The Psychology of Saving', sub:'Overcoming Mental Barriers to Saving', body:`Saving is not primarily a math problem — it is a psychology problem. Understanding the mental barriers to saving helps you overcome them.\n\nKey Psychological Barriers:\n\n1. Present Bias:\nWe overvalue immediate rewards vs future rewards.\nFix: Automate savings so the decision is made once, not daily.\n\n2. Lifestyle Inflation:\nSpending rises automatically with income.\nFix: Save 50% of every income increase before lifestyle adjusts.\n\n3. Social Comparison:\n"Keeping up with the Joneses" — spending to match peers.\nFix: Compare your current self to your past self, not to others.\n\n4. Mental Accounting:\nTreating money differently based on source (bonus = spend freely).\nFix: All money is equal — treat bonus same as salary.\n\n5. Optimism Bias:\n"I will save more next month" — perpetual delay.\nFix: Start today with any amount. Perfection is the enemy of good.\n\n6. Hedonic Adaptation:\nGetting used to higher lifestyle and wanting more.\nFix: Practice gratitude and contentment with current lifestyle.`, points:['Present bias: We overvalue now vs future — automation fixes this','Lifestyle inflation: Save 50% of every income increase immediately','Social comparison: Compare to your past self, not to others','Mental accounting: Treat bonus same as salary — all money is equal','Optimism bias: Start today with any amount — do not wait for perfect conditions'], highlight:'💡 "The enemy of saving is not lack of money — it is lack of systems." Build systems that make saving automatic and spending conscious.', example:'Deepak got a ₹20,000 salary raise. He immediately increased his SIP by ₹10,000 (50% of raise) before his lifestyle could adjust. 5 years later, he does not miss the ₹10,000 — but his portfolio is ₹7.5 Lakhs richer.' },
  { pg:11, title:'Saving vs Investing', sub:'When to Save and When to Invest', body:`Saving and investing are different activities with different purposes. Knowing when to save and when to invest is crucial for financial success.\n\nSaving:\n- Purpose: Capital preservation, liquidity, short-term goals\n- Risk: Very low to none\n- Returns: 4-7.5%\n- Time horizon: 0-3 years\n- Vehicles: Savings account, FD, liquid fund, RD\n\nInvesting:\n- Purpose: Wealth creation, beating inflation, long-term goals\n- Risk: Moderate to high\n- Returns: 10-15%+ (equity)\n- Time horizon: 3+ years\n- Vehicles: Stocks, mutual funds, real estate, gold\n\nThe Priority Order:\n1. Emergency fund (save first)\n2. High-interest debt payoff (guaranteed return = interest rate saved)\n3. Tax-advantaged investing (ELSS, NPS, PPF)\n4. Long-term investing (equity mutual funds)\n5. Short-term goal saving (debt funds, FD)\n\nThe Inflation Problem:\nInflation in India: ~6% annually\nSavings account return: 3.5%\nReal return: -2.5% (you are losing purchasing power)\nConclusion: Long-term money MUST be invested, not just saved.`, points:['Saving = capital preservation for 0-3 year needs','Investing = wealth creation for 3+ year goals','Inflation (6%) destroys savings account returns (3.5%) over time','Priority: Emergency fund → Debt payoff → Tax-advantaged investing → Long-term investing','Never keep long-term money in savings account — inflation destroys it'], highlight:'💡 ₹10 Lakhs in savings account for 20 years at 3.5% = ₹19.9 Lakhs. Same amount invested at 12% = ₹96.5 Lakhs. Inflation-adjusted: savings account loses value; equity creates wealth.', example:'Suresh kept ₹20 Lakhs in FD for 10 years (7% return) = ₹39.3 Lakhs. If invested in Nifty 50 (14% CAGR) = ₹74.3 Lakhs. Opportunity cost of over-saving in FD: ₹35 Lakhs.' },
  { pg:12, title:'Saving for Retirement', sub:'Why You Must Start Now', body:`Retirement saving is the most important long-term financial goal. Yet most Indians are completely unprepared for retirement.\n\nThe Retirement Reality:\n- Average Indian retirement age: 60\n- Average life expectancy: 75-80 years\n- Retirement duration: 15-20 years\n- Monthly expenses at retirement (inflation-adjusted): 2-3x current expenses\n\nThe Retirement Corpus Formula:\nRequired corpus = Annual expenses at retirement × 25 (4% withdrawal rule)\n\nExample:\nCurrent monthly expenses: ₹50,000\nAt retirement (30 years, 6% inflation): ₹2,87,000/month = ₹34.4 Lakh/year\nRequired corpus: ₹34.4L × 25 = ₹8.6 Crore\n\nRetirement Savings Vehicles:\n1. EPF (Employee Provident Fund): 8.15% guaranteed, tax-free\n2. PPF (Public Provident Fund): 7.1%, tax-free, 15-year lock-in\n3. NPS (National Pension System): Market-linked, tax benefits\n4. Equity Mutual Funds: Highest returns for long-term\n\nThe Power of Starting Early:\n₹5,000/month from age 25 at 12% = ₹1.76 Crore at 60\n₹5,000/month from age 35 at 12% = ₹52 Lakhs at 60`, points:['Required retirement corpus = Annual expenses × 25 (4% rule)','EPF: 8.15% guaranteed, tax-free — maximize this first','PPF: 7.1% tax-free, excellent for conservative portion','NPS: Tax benefits + market returns for aggressive portion','Starting at 25 vs 35 for same monthly amount = 3.4x more corpus'], highlight:'💡 The 4% Rule: A ₹1 Crore corpus can sustain ₹4 Lakh/year withdrawal indefinitely (inflation-adjusted). For ₹50,000/month retirement income, you need ₹1.5 Crore corpus.', example:'Anita starts ₹10,000/month retirement SIP at age 25 (12% CAGR). At 60: ₹3.5 Crore. Her colleague Ravi starts at 35: ₹1.04 Crore. Same monthly investment, 10-year head start = 3.4x more wealth.' },
  { pg:13, title:'Saving Challenges and Techniques', sub:'Gamify Your Way to Better Savings', body:`Making saving fun and engaging increases the likelihood of sticking with it. Here are proven saving challenges and techniques.\n\n1. The 52-Week Challenge:\nWeek 1: Save ₹100. Week 2: ₹200. Week 3: ₹300... Week 52: ₹5,200.\nTotal saved: ₹1,37,800 in one year.\n\n2. The No-Spend Challenge:\nChoose one category (dining out, shopping, entertainment) and spend ₹0 for 30 days.\nTypical savings: ₹3,000-10,000/month.\n\n3. The Round-Up Method:\nRound up every purchase to nearest ₹100 and save the difference.\nExample: ₹347 purchase → save ₹53. Adds up to ₹2,000-5,000/month.\n\n4. The 24-Hour Rule:\nFor any non-essential purchase above ₹1,000, wait 24 hours before buying.\nEliminate 50-70% of impulse purchases.\n\n5. The Savings Jar:\nPhysically put ₹100 in a jar every day. Visual progress is motivating.\n₹100/day = ₹36,500/year.\n\n6. The Savings Buddy:\nFind a friend with similar savings goals. Check in weekly.\nAccountability increases success rate by 65%.`, points:['52-week challenge: Start with ₹100, increase by ₹100 weekly = ₹1.38L/year','No-spend challenge: Zero spending in one category for 30 days','24-hour rule: Wait 24 hours before any non-essential purchase above ₹1,000','Round-up method: Save the difference when rounding up purchases','Savings buddy: Accountability partner increases success rate by 65%'], highlight:'💡 The 24-hour rule eliminates 50-70% of impulse purchases. Before buying anything non-essential above ₹1,000, sleep on it. Most impulses disappear overnight.', example:'Kiran tried the no-spend challenge for dining out in January. Saved ₹8,500 that month. Invested it in SIP. Realized she did not miss dining out as much as she thought. Now saves ₹5,000/month consistently.' },
  { pg:14, title:'Tracking and Reviewing Savings Progress', sub:'What Gets Measured Gets Managed', body:`Tracking your savings progress is essential for staying motivated and on course. What you measure, you manage.\n\nKey Metrics to Track Monthly:\n\n1. Savings Rate:\nSavings ÷ Income × 100\nTarget: 20%+ (30%+ is excellent)\n\n2. Emergency Fund Progress:\nCurrent balance ÷ Target × 100\nTarget: 6 months of expenses\n\n3. Net Worth:\nTotal assets − Total liabilities\nShould increase every month\n\n4. Goal Progress:\nCurrent savings ÷ Goal amount × 100\nFor each specific goal\n\nTools for Tracking:\n- Spreadsheet (Google Sheets): Most flexible\n- Walnut app: Automatic expense tracking\n- Money Manager app: Comprehensive budgeting\n- ET Money: Investment + expense tracking\n\nMonthly Review Process (30 minutes on 1st of month):\n1. Update net worth spreadsheet\n2. Review savings rate vs target\n3. Check goal progress\n4. Identify biggest expense categories\n5. Plan adjustments for next month`, points:['Track savings rate monthly: Target 20%+, excellent 30%+','Update net worth monthly — should increase every month','Use apps: Walnut, Money Manager, ET Money for automatic tracking','Monthly review: 30 minutes on 1st of month','Celebrate milestones: First ₹1L saved, first ₹5L, first ₹10L'], highlight:'💡 "What gets measured gets managed." Investors who track their net worth monthly accumulate 2-3x more wealth than those who do not track.', example:'Divya started tracking net worth monthly in January 2022: ₹2.3 Lakhs. By December 2024: ₹8.7 Lakhs. Seeing the number grow every month motivated her to save more. Tracking changed her behavior.' },
  { pg:15, title:'Saving Strategies Action Plan', sub:'Your Complete Savings Transformation', body:`You have completed the Saving Strategies course. Here is your complete action plan to transform your savings immediately.\n\nThis Week:\n✓ Calculate your current savings rate (savings ÷ income × 100)\n✓ Open a liquid fund account (Groww, Zerodha Coin, Paytm Money)\n✓ Set up auto-transfer of 10% of income on payday\n✓ Do a subscription audit — cancel anything unused\n\nThis Month:\n✓ Build ₹25,000 mini emergency fund\n✓ Try the 24-hour rule for all non-essential purchases above ₹1,000\n✓ Create sinking funds for your top 3 planned expenses\n✓ Track every expense for 30 days\n\nThis Quarter:\n✓ Increase savings rate by 5% (reduce one expense category)\n✓ Build emergency fund to 1 month expenses\n✓ Start ₹1,000/month SIP for long-term goals\n✓ Find a savings accountability buddy\n\nThis Year:\n✓ Build emergency fund to 3 months expenses\n✓ Increase SIP to 15-20% of income\n✓ Review and optimize all savings vehicles\n✓ Take the quiz to earn your Saving Strategies badge\n\nRemember: The best savings strategy is the one you actually follow consistently.`, points:['Start with 10% savings rate and increase by 1% every 3 months','Build emergency fund in phases: ₹25K → 1 month → 3 months → 6 months','Automate everything — savings, SIP, bills, goal contributions','Track savings rate and net worth monthly','Celebrate every milestone — savings is a lifelong journey'], highlight:'💡 "A small saving today is a large fortune tomorrow." Start with whatever you can — even ₹500/month. The habit matters more than the amount.', example:'Students who implement even 3 of these strategies in the first week report saving an average of ₹4,000-8,000 more per month within 90 days. What 3 strategies will you implement today?' },
];
